\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/st_group.moments}{Moment statistics}}
\begin{definition}\label{st_group.moments}
\uses{st_group.definition}
\textbf{Moment statistics} refers to moments of random variables associated to a \hyperref[st_group.definition]{Sato-Tate group} $G$, where the distribution of the random variable is defined using the pushforward of the Haar measure of $G$.

Standard random variables one can associated to $G$ include the coefficients $a_i$ of the characteristic polynomial $\sum a_ix^i$ of a random matrix $g\in G$, the $i$th symmetric function $e_i$ of the eigenvalues $\lambda_j$ of $g$, and the powers sums $s_i:=\sum \lambda_j^i$ which can be expressed as polynomials in the $a_i$ or $e_i$ via the Newton identities.

The \textbf{moment sequence} of $a_i$ (or any random variable) is the integer sequence $(\mathrm{E}[a_i^0], \mathrm{E}[a_i^1],\mathrm{E}[a_i^2]\ldots)$; the convention of including the zeroth moment $\mathrm{E}[a_i^0]=1$ facilitates the computation of moment sequences of products of independent random variables by taking binomial convolutions.

\end{definition}


